{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584223"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:42:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:42:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14433"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14433"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7128"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113498"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7128"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14433"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95515"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4905"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"9850"},{"type":"tags","id":"10290"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17031"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17144"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46667"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113498"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman is participating in a physiology study examining autonomic effects on cardiac electrophysiology. She is healthy and takes no regular medicines. Baseline heart rate is 70 beats per minute with normal atrioventricular conduction. The researchers sequentially apply selective autonomic receptor agonists and record changes in nodal action potential characteristics and atrioventricular conduction time.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the combined effects on the sinoatrial (SA) node and atrioventricular (AV) node produced by sympathetic stimulation via beta-adrenergic receptors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreases phase 4 depolarisation in the SA node and lengthens AV nodal conduction time","Increases phase 4 depolarisation in the SA node and lengthens AV nodal conduction time","Decreases phase 4 depolarisation in the SA node and shortens AV nodal conduction time","Increases phase 4 depolarisation in the SA node and shortens AV nodal conduction time","No change in phase 4 depolarisation in the SA node and lengthens AV nodal conduction time"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAutonomic inputs modulate cardiac pacemaking and conduction primarily through effects on nodal tissue ion channels. Sympathetic activation via beta-adrenergic receptors increases intracellular cyclic AMP and protein kinase A activity, which enhances funny current (I\u003Csub\u003Ef\u003C/sub\u003E) and L-type calcium current (I\u003Csub\u003ECa,L\u003C/sub\u003E) in nodal cells. This steepens phase 4 depolarisation in the sinoatrial (SA) node, increasing firing rate, and augments conduction through the atrioventricular (AV) node by increasing calcium-dependent upstroke velocity and reducing nodal refractoriness, thereby shortening AV nodal conduction time (atrioventricular nodal delay/PR segment).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases phase 4 depolarisation in the SA node and lengthens AV nodal conduction time\u003C/strong\u003E describes the opposite of sympathetic effects; this pattern aligns with parasympathetic (muscarinic) influences.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases phase 4 depolarisation in the SA node and lengthens AV nodal conduction time\u003C/strong\u003E correctly identifies the SA node effect but incorrectly suggests that sympathetic stimulation impairs AV nodal conduction; in reality it facilitates conduction and reduces delay.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases phase 4 depolarisation in the SA node and shortens AV nodal conduction time\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly describes the SA node effect while correctly identifying the AV nodal response to sympathetic stimulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases phase 4 depolarisation in the SA node and shortens AV nodal conduction time\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because beta-adrenergic stimulation increases the slope of diastolic depolarisation and speeds conduction through the AV node, reducing atrioventricular nodal delay.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo change in phase 4 depolarisation in the SA node and lengthens AV nodal conduction time\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because sympathetic stimulation significantly affects both SA node automaticity and AV nodal conduction properties.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sympathetic stimulation increases sinoatrial node phase 4 slope and enhances atrioventricular nodal conduction via beta-adrenergic effects on cyclic AMP and calcium currents.","Parasympathetic stimulation hyperpolarises nodal tissue and reduces conduction via acetylcholine-activated potassium current and reduced L-type calcium current."],"references":["Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Cooke, J., Di Pietro, F., Diversi, T., ... \u0026 Summers, S.. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 3rd Asia-Pacific Edition. 2022. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Gordan R, Gwathmey JK, Xie LH. Autonomic and endocrine control of cardiovascular function. World J Cardiol. 2015 Apr 26;7(4):204-14. doi: 10.4330/wjc.v7.i4.204. PMID: 25914789; PMCID: PMC4404375.","J\u00e4nig W. Mechanisms of Neuroeffector Transmission. In: The Integrative Action of the Autonomic Nervous System: Neurobiology of Homeostasis. Cambridge University Press; 2022:200-226. Available from:  https://doi.org/10.1017/9781108778411.011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95515"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14433"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95515"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-12T12:49:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-12T12:52:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7128"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113498"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nu